M|rules|title: Build Index Maps for Repeated Lookups
M|rules|impact: LOW-MEDIUM
M|rules|impactDescription: 1M ops to 2K ops
M|rules|tags: javascript, map, indexing, optimization, performance
M|rules|Multiple `.find()` calls by the same key should use a Map.
M|rules|**Incorrect (O(n) per lookup):**
M|rules|```typescript
M|rules|function processOrders(orders: Order[], users: User[]) {
M|rules|return orders.map(order => ({
M|rules|...order,
M|rules|user: users.find(u => u.id === order.userId)
M|rules|}))
M|rules|}
M|rules|```
M|rules|**Correct (O(1) per lookup):**
M|rules|```typescript
M|rules|function processOrders(orders: Order[], users: User[]) {
M|rules|const userById = new Map(users.map(u => [u.id, u]))
M|rules|return orders.map(order => ({
M|rules|...order,
M|rules|user: userById.get(order.userId)
M|rules|}))
M|rules|}
M|rules|```
M|rules|Build map once (O(n)), then all lookups are O(1).
M|rules|For 1000 orders × 1000 users: 1M ops → 2K ops.